Right, here's the explanation :)

The new Amiga is strictly, an OS (rather than hardware + OS) and is based on
Tao's Elate system.  The Elate system has the rather neat feature of a VP,
or Virtual Processor....so when you write for Elate, your programs are
stored as VP binaries (as opposed to 68k binaries, x86 binaries and so on)
and when run, te VP translates your program into native binary code on the
fly.  This means that you have complete hardware abstraction, as long as
people are using the Elate system, as the only difference between an x86
Elate system and a PPC Elate system, is that for the x86 the VP translates
to x86 code, and for the PPC the VP translates to PPC code.

What this means, is that you can develop on an x86, and anyone around the
world can run that program on their Elate system.  But if you're worried
about speed, you need not be....apparently the VP van translate VP code
/faster/ than the hard-disk can spool the code from disk.  But if you still
want to make opimisations, they have a system whereby you can create (for
example) an x86 binary, and if run on an x86 machine it will use that code
(if not it uses the generic VP version).

It's also supposed to have a very, amiga-like API.  Oh, and Tao's Java VM
(named Intent) is said to be the fastest around

Does that make sense?

