Just to get you up to speed on Amigas future..

(Wow, Rick beat me to this but I think i ca compliment his
explanation with some ovelapping stuff here and there...)

Amiga NG is a software ONLY thing. Amiga Inc are in the software
market. However, they have very good links with hardware makers
including the top of the market CPU, GFX card and general hardware
people. This means they can orchestrate the design of a 'first'
new Amiga towards the end of this year. Bill McEwen called this
the 'AmigaOne'. It's going to be fairly high performance but
very low cost. This wont by any means be the 'standard' Amiga
but it will be the first of a series of licensed machines built
by third parties. Eventually you'll see official licensed Amigas
in all shapes and sizes from the smallest hand held to big
server boxes and of course every desktop design you can imagine.

In addition to these hardware solutions, the new Amiga will also
run on top of all major OS's including Linux (which the developer
kit shows), BeOS, MacOS, Windows, QNX etc. Amiga Inc claim they
can support any new OS in a matter of a month (or two). As well
as this 'any OS you like' concept, there's also an 'any CPU' thing
going on. Amiga will run happily on x86, PPC, MIPS, Transmeta,
Alpha etc. Once again, any new CPU that turns up can be
supported in two months. So there's just no stopping Amiga!

The development base of the new Amiga is based on three main
programming languages, these are Java, C/C++ and VP. The VP
thing is the most interesting part. VP, standing for Virtual
Processor is an abstraction of any real CPU that Amiga can
run on top of. You code in 'VP Assembler' and the code will
run on Amiga no matter which CPU the machine has. The Virtual
Processor code is for an abstracted CPU, the OS will execute
this code which is converted (very quickly) before running on
the native CPU. The VP code is very much like Asm code with
some clever macro's. The code can be made to look like
regular Asm but an at times look very much like a higher
level language such as Basic/C with it's if/endif and while
loops. rather than comparing registers the old Asm way
you can do it like "if p0 == 0". The main thing to realize is
that VP will run on any machine. And that's why VP is form of
tools on the new Ami.

I'm not totally sure how C++ compiling works on the new Ami
but afaik if takes C/C++ code and turns it into VP byte code.
This means the compiled C will run on any machine just like
hand crafted VP Assember. This is what a potential new Blitz
language would have to do. Amiga Inc claim in the SDK that they
are actively seeking "Ingenious new Amiga specific languages"
to compliment the standard Java and C++ languages. The SDK
contains a huge amount of documentation. The manual alone is
quite an impressive introduction to the impressive new Kernel
and the current Languages + VP. The manual is 300 pages
but the CD contains the equivalent of a further 1200 pages of
documentation in PDF format.

The new Amiga OS does have many things similar to the original
OS. Things such as Arexx, Message Ports, tiny efficient Kernel
design and Boing Balls are just a start!

I guess I've only really touched on Amiga developments here
with a short description of the whole picture. I don't really
wont to get into any heavy discussusions regarding the way
Amiga is going or viability of all this. I'm very confident
about the Amigas future, we'll see a lot of real great things
happen well before the end of the year. I now feel that there's
