Perhaps not, remember that last box in the compiler options window "Full debug 
info". Turn that on and extra debugging information is put into your executable 
(but not the debugger, unless you highlight the runtime debugger box) for 
things like function addresses, variables and things.

> But wouldn't this add the usual slowdowns you get from running in debug mode
> into the profiles, thus confusing the issue?  (Since some stuff seems to slow
> down a lot with the debugger on, and other stuff doesn't show much of a
> slowdown...)

Yeah, if the runtime debugger was on, I'm pretty sure it would screw up some 
results. Example being if you turn on the Assembly debugger and run an assembly 
function, it can run slower than some Basic code :( Plus, not all commands have 
debugging code in them, so you'd get a skewed result.


