@NODE "Mail_54" " Re: Multiplying Longwords "
From: David McMinn <dave@satanicdreams.com>
Date: 07-25-00 14:11:12
Subject: @{b}Re: Multiplying Longwords@{ub}

Tony Rolfe's head burst.
All we could scrape off the wall was Multiplying Longwords.

> Some long time ago I remember reading something about using an 8-byte
> field to store the result of a multiplication of two longwords.  (Not
> in Blitz, just some generic thing many years back).

There are 64bit maths functions in some of the Amiga maths libraries (also
utility.library).

You'd probably have to write a function to interface with it and call it in ASM
though, but it would look something like this:

Statement SignedMult{a.l, b.l, &answer.Result}
    getreg  a6,UtilityBase        ; utility.library base
    JSR     -198(a6)              ; call SMult64 (I hope the LVO is right)
    move.l  d3,a0
    move.l  d0,(a0)
    move.l  d1,4(a0)
    asmexit
End Statement

There's also unsigned functions, divide instructions, modulus instructions, all
in 32 or 64 bit.

> And, then, how do I use this Answer in a division to get a long result
> at the end?

If the number is small enough, you can just use the second longword in the
result, otherwise you might need to use some more of the 64bit number functions
in utility.library.

