@NODE "Mail_70" " Re: Reading bits. "
From: David McMinn <D.Mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Date: 07-03-00 12:25:45
Subject: @{b}Re: Reading bits.@{ub}

Hi Gareth

> I know that you can read in individual BYTES using Blitz, but is it possible to
> read in individual BITS from a file?

Of course, but you need to work with bytes and then mask out the bits you are 
not interested in.

> I can't see any commands to do it. Would reading in a byte and then using
> Mid$() on it work? Probably not :-)

No, you'd read in a byte and then mask stuff out, using logical operations, 
such as AND and OR.

> I'm trying to get data from MP3 files about bitrates and things and they are
> stored in BITS according to the documents I have.
> 
> For example:
> 
> AAAAAAAA AAAxxxxx (A represents the frame sync in an MP3 file)

> That is 11 bits, and when set total 255 (FF) and in AZap, which only appears to

No, I think you'll find that when you have 11 bits that are all set the value 
will be 2047.

In the above case, you'd want to read in a word, so that you read in all the 
bits you need (plus any extra but we can discard them) and you are reading in a 
multiple of 8 (cos you can only read in full bytes).

Assuming you are using normal Blitz file commands:

; read in the two bytes which contain bitrate
bitrate.w = Cvi(Inkey$(2))
; shift the bitrate value right by 5 binary places
bitrate = bitrate LSR 5
; bitrate (shown in binary) will now look like 00000AAA AAAAAAAA - the xxxxx
; has been shifted out of the right end of the number and discarded
NPrint "decimal: ",bitrate
NPrint "hex:     $",Hex$(bitrate)
NPrint "binary:  %",Bin$(bitrate)

One more consideration you might need to check is the endian format of the 
numbers. This is the way the CPU stores the data in memory (and would probably 
be the same in the file). There are two options: big endian and little endian. 
Big endian is the way 68k stores numbers, with the most significant (biggest) 
byte (MSB) first in memory. Little endian is the way x86 stores numbers and 
this is the least significant (smallest) first (LSB).

The endian type has no affect on a number which is a single byte in size, i.e. 
hex number $69, would be stored in memory as "69" either way.

For example, if we have the hex number $DEAD, then DE would be the MSB and AD 
would be the LSB. The number would be stored as "DE AD" on 68k and "AD DE" on 
x86.

If we had the number $DEADBEEF then DE would be MSB and EF would be LSB. On a 
68k it would be stored as "DE AD BE EF" and on x86 it would be stored as "EF BE 
AD DE".

So, if after trying printing the value and it looks totally wrong, it may be 
because its stored as a little endian number. To convert a word between endian 
types, use this function:

Function.w EndianWord{val.w}
    ROL.w #8,d0
    AsmExit
End Function

And for longwords, use this:

Function.l EndianLong{val.l}
    ROL.w #8,d0
	SWAP d0
    ROL.w #8,d0
    AsmExit
End Function

> show single BYTES, it does indeed come out as FF, and NOT 11111111 which I am
> wanting :-)

FF(hex) is the same number as 11111111(bin) just written in a different way. To 
the computer it is the same. To you it is the same, just written different. As 
is 255(dec). You just need to stick it in a variable and then display it the 
way you want (binary, hex, decimal, etc).

