> GG> scared me off but you've lost me :-) I have no idea about ASM and stuff like

Nngh. Its not ASM, its binary logic. And you don't need to know ASM to use the 
endian functions. BTW, this may be another long answer, but its easier than the 
last one I wrote.

> Not too hard.  If you wanna see if bit 0 is set (1), use something like If
> variable.b AND 1=1, if you wanna see if bit 7 is set (128) use If variable.b AND
> 128=128.  If you wanna see if bits 3 and 4 are set (8 + 16) use If variable.b
> AND 24=24.
> 
> If you want to mask out the lower 5 bits, variableb.l=variablea.w AND 65504.

BTW, instead of using decimal for creating masks or doing other logical 
operations, its a lot easier to use hex or binary.

variableb.l=variablea.w AND $FFE0

variableb.l=variablea.w AND %1111111111100000  

Basically, the rules are:

if you want to set a bit to 0, you AND that bit with 0. If you AND a bit with 
1, that bit is left as it is. This you can use to mask out bits by setting the 
unwanted bits to 0.

If you want to set a bit to 1 you OR that bit with 1. If you OR a bit with 0, 
that bit is left alone.

If you NOT a bit, you toggle that bit (0->1 and 1->0) although, you cannot work 
at a bit level with NOT by itself, i.e. it will toggle all the bits in your 
variable at once.

If you EOR (exclusive OR) a bit with 1, that bit will be toggled. If you EOR a 
bit with 0, that bit is left as it was.

If you LSR (logical shift right), the number gets shifted right by however, 
many bits you specify. The bits on the left (MSbit) get set to 0.

If you LSL (logical shift left), the number gets shifted left by however, many 
bits you specify. The bits on the right (LSbit) get set to 0.

e.g.

;---8<-----8<-----8<-----
Statement ShowVar{var.w, info$}
    ; this just shows some text, and the variable in hex, binary and decimal.
    ; the right$ commands are there because we are using WORD sized variables
    ; but the Hex$ command and Bin$ command always assume LONG sized variables.
    NPrint RSet$(info$, 34),": $",Right$(Hex$(var),4)," 
%",Right$(Bin$(var),16)," ",var
End Statement

NPrint "All values follow on from each other"

var1.w = $FFFF
ShowVar{var1, "Original value"}

var2.w = var1 AND %1111000011110000
ShowVar{var2, "Set some bits to 0"}

var3.w = var2 OR %0000011000000110
ShowVar{var3, "Set some bits to 1"}

var4.w = NOT(var3)
ShowVar{var4, "Toggle ALL bits"}

var5.w = var4 EOR %0011110000000000
ShowVar{var5, "Toggle SOME bits"}

var6.w = var5 LSR 3
ShowVar{var6, "Shift all bits right by 3 places"}

var7.w = var5 LSL 5
ShowVar{var7, "Shift all bits left by 5 places"}
ClickMouse
End
;---8<-----8<-----8<-----

