I mean of course "inverse respectively" here.

To clear up any confusion I might have caused:

If you have a binary number %00101001 = 1+8+32 = 41 and then shift it to
the left you get %01010010 = 2+16+64 = 82. If you shift it the other way,
then you get %00010100 = 4+16 = 20. These are simple multiply and divides
by two - obviously in the second case this doesn't work *entirely*
correctly, but we are just working with integers here.

This is exactly equivalent to decimal counting, where shifting to the left
is the same as a multiply by ten. Thus 100 LSL 1 = 1000 (if the syntax is
correct). The only difference is that binary is base 2 and so the shift to
a higher place results in a multiplication by 2.

Cheers,

