Hi Tony

> I Tried to do a test for Ctrl_C inside a VBlank interrupt., using
> David's SetSignal_ test.

<snip>

> Any thoughts???

Obviously "End" can't be used inside an interrupt, probably because the code 
isn't called on your task or something.

Anyway, perhaps the solution would be just to set a flag in the interrupt and 
then check for that flag in your main code. It would be a lot quicker just 
checking a flag than doing the whole check for the setsignal each loop, i.e.

SETINT 5
   If <<test for Ctrl_C>> Then ctrlc=-1
end setint

.loop
    ; do stuff
    if ctrlc
        ; do whatever
    end if
    ; repeat loop

This would also have the advantage that you could do different things in 
different places in your program when ctrl-c was pressed. For example, in the 
main loop or whatever, it may quit the whole program, but in a sub-processing 
loop thing (for example, sorting all your customers) it might just quit the 
sort and go back to the main loop.

Or you could just use it to quit the program I suppose :)

